<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12016d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12016d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12016d"> 16(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">D</font> changes course</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">L&apos;estuaire du Cou&euml;snon, qui s&eacute;pare la Bretagne de la Normandie, trace maintenant son lit sablonneux &agrave; gauche du Mont. Autrefois, il passait &agrave; droite. Aussi, Bretons et Normands se sont-ils disput&eacute; le rocher porteur du sanctuaire et s&eacute;jour de l&apos;archange protecteur de la France. Les Bretons disaient: <br>Le Cou&euml;snon, dans sa folie, A mis le Mont en Normandie. <br>Les Normands ripostaient: <br>Si bonne n&apos;&eacute;tait Normandie, <br>Saint Michel ne s&apos;y serait mis. <br><font color="green">[The estuary of the Cou&euml;snon, which separates Brittany from Normandy, now traces its sandy bed to the left of the Mont. Before, it passed on the right. Thus Bretons and Normands have argued who own the rock containing the sanctuary and home of the Angel-Protector of France. The Bretons said: <br>The Cou&euml;snon, in its folly <br>Has put the Mont in Normandy. <br>The Normands replied: <br>If Normandy hadn&apos;t been good <br>Saint Michel would not have gone there.]</font> <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLL"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1892) 126-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
